      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://crowcello.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Caitlin Crow</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/12/december-7/#comment-60009"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-07T15:33:35-05:00">Wednesday, December 7, 2016 at 3:33 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Dearest Molly,</p>
<p>(may I call you dearest Molly even though we&#8217;ve never met?)<br />
I learned a really fantastic Italian word the other day: commuovere, a verb meaning &#8220;to be moved in a heartwarming way, usually relating to a story that moved you to tears&#8221;. I&#8217;ve read your blog since its inception&#8211;at this point I can&#8217;t even remember how I found it; Bon Appetit, maybe?&#8211;and it, followed by your books and podcast, have been welcome constants in my life these past 12 years.  I&#8217;ve never commented and am late to your November 30 post, but I just wanted to thank you for it and your most eloquent and open writing. I had a &#8220;sexual fluidity experience&#8221; (ha) of my own in 2011. The short version of the story is that I suddenly fell deeply in love with a man (my now husband) after having only female partners my entire adult life; a sort of reverse coming out, if you will. These revelations send shock waves through us and through our communities, but we do sort it out. It gets better. Much love to you and your family.</p>
    </div>

      <ol class="children">
  <li id="comment-60366" class="comment odd alt depth-2">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.2besetfree.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Karen</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/12/december-7/#comment-60366"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-12-21T12:16:05-05:00">Wednesday, December 21, 2016 at 12:16 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I too have been reading Orangette since it&#8217;s beginning, and Molly your writing has always given me great pleasure. I wanted to tag on to Caitlin&#8217;s comment for two reasons; first, I can echo all of it. I identified as gay since a child, yet at 21 fell in love with a man. We were together 14 years, he knew he was an exception and agreed to enjoy our relationship together until/if ever it became time to move on, for him or myself. That time happened last year, and I am now with the female love of my life. Yep, it rocked several boats, yep it was as beautiful and as inspiring and as truly sweet as one could imagine and also equally as painful and terrifying and gut wrenching as one could imagine. He is still one of my best friends, we are still active in each other&#8217;s lives and I love him in a big way- and this was hard for a lot of people to understand, because it is nearly wholly un-relatable. But time provides any needed evidence as it marches on and things do sort out! Much love to you Molly. Second; For some of us, it&#8217;s about more than gender. The soul of whom we love shines to us and pulls us in. It is a needed necessary experience. Change comes before us in infinite possible expressions and it is truly the work of our lives to step forward and say Yes. One can be afraid, but when Love acts as the thing that goes before all else, the outcome is glorious.</p>
    </div>

